lreportof01west/biennialreportof01west.pdf | archive-date = 1 March 2020 | author-link = West Virginia Department of Education | oclc = 1041611348}}\n* {{cite journal |last= Woodson |first= Carter G. | author-link = Carter G. Woodson | date= July 1921 |title= Notes |url= https://ia801703.us.archive.org/32/items/jstor-2713764/2713764.pdf |journal= [[The Journal of African American History|The Journal of Negro History]] |volume= 6 |issue= 3 |pages=380\u20131 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200301024144/https://ia801703.us.archive.org/32/items/jstor-2713764/2713764.pdf |archive-date= 1 March 2020 |access-date= 1 March 2020 | via = [[Internet Archive]] | publisher = [[Association for the Study of African American Life and History|Association for the Study of Negro Life and History]] | location = Washington, D.C. | ref = harv|doi= 10.1086/JNHv6n3p380 }}\n* {{cite journal |last= Woodson |first= Carter G. | author-link = Carter G. Woodson | date= January 1922 |title= Early Negro Education in West Virginia |url= https://ia601903.us.archive.org/16/items/jstor-2713579/2713579.pdf |journal= [[The Journal of African American History|The Journal of Negro History]] |volume= 7 |issue= 1 |pages=23\u201363 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229201551/https://ia601903.us.archive.org/16/items/jstor-2713579/2713579.pdf |archive-date= 29 February 2020 |access-date= 29 February 2020 | via = [[Internet Archive]] | publisher = [[Association for the Study of African American Life and History|Association for the Study of Negro Life and History]] | location = Washington, D.C. | ref = harv|doi= 10.2307/2713579 |jstor= 2713579 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Woodson |first= Carter G. | author-link = Carter G. Woodson |year = 2000 | editor-last1 = Conyers | editor-first1 = James L., Jr. | title = Carter G. Woodson: A Historical Reader |publisher = [[Garland Science|Garland Publishing, Inc.]] |location = New York |isbn =  | oclc = 1148191420 |url = https://archive.org/details/cartergwoodsonhi0000wood/ |accessdate = |ref = harv |via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, John Warren}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American academics]]\n[[Category:African-American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:African-American university presidents]]\n[[Category:Educators from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Educators from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Morehouse College alumni]]\n[[Category:Morehouse College faculty]]\n[[Category:NAACP activists]]\n[[Category:National Education Association people]]\n[[Category:Order of the Star of Africa]]\n[[Category:People from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:People from Englewood, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Institute, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Milledgeville, Georgia]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Presidents of West Virginia State University]]\n[[Category:UNESCO officials]]\n[[Category:United States Department of State officials]]\n[[Category:United States National Science Foundation officials]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:YMCA leaders]]\n", "name_user": "West Virginian", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExpansion and improvement of the campus and curriculum:reorder citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Warren_Davis_(college_president)"}
{"title_page": "Kingston (1780 ship)", "text_new": "{{other ships|Kingston (ship)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2018}}\n{| {{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image =\n| Ship caption =\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship country=United Kingdom\n| Ship flag={{shipboxflag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n| Ship name = ''Kingston''\n| Ship namesake =\n| Ship owner =*1780:J. Collard\n* 1798:D. Bennett\n* 1803: Alexander & John Gibbon; Matthew Swain\n| Ship operator =\n| Ship ordered =\n| Ship builder = Bristol\n| Ship original cost =\n| Ship laid down =\n| Ship launched = 1780\n| Ship acquired =\n| Ship commissioned =\n| Ship decommissioned =\n| Ship in service =\n| Ship out of service =\n| Ship renamed =\n| Ship struck =\n| Ship reinstated =\n| Ship honours =\n| Ship honors =\n| Ship captured =\n| Ship fate = Last listed 1819\n| Ship status =\n| Ship notes =\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header =\n| Header caption =\n| Ship class =\n| Ship tons burthen=287,<ref name=LoM>[http://www.1812privateers.org/Great%20Britain/marque1793-1815.pdf Letter of Marque, p.71 - accessed 25 July 2017.]</ref> or 293,<ref name=LR1799/> or 300<ref name=LR1780/><ref name=RS1818/> ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]])\n| Ship length ={{cvt|95|ft|0|in|m|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=Stanbury>Stanbury ''et al.'' (2015), App.7.</ref>\n| Ship beam ={{cvt|27|ft|3|in|m|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=Stanbury/>\n| Ship draught =\n| Ship draft =\n| Ship hold depth =\n| Ship propulsion =\n| Ship sail plan =\n| Ship complement =*1800:26<ref name=LoM/>\n* 1803:18\n| Ship armament =*1780:20 \u00d7 9-pounder + 4 \u00d7 6-pounder guns<ref name=LR1780/>\n* 1799:2 \u00d7 4-pounder guns + 10 \u00d7 9-pounder [[carronades]]<ref name=LR1799/>\n* 1800:12 \u00d7 9&4-pounder cannons<ref name=LoM/>\n* 1815:8 \u00d7 6-pounder [[carronades]]<ref name=RS1815/>\n| Ship notes = Two decks and three masts\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Kingston''''' was launched at Bristol in 1780 as a [[West Indiaman]]. From 1798 she made ten voyages as a whaler. She then briefly sailed between England and Quebec, and is last listed in 1819.\n\n==Career==\n''Kingston'' first appeared in ''[[Lloyd's Register]]'' in 1780 with J. Fowler, master, J. Collard, owner, and trade Bristol\u2013Jamaica.<ref name=LR1780>[https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015065522800?urlappend=%3Bseq=162 ''Lloyd's Register'' (1780), \"K\" Supple. pages, Seq. \u2116K80.]</ref> For the next 18 or so years she continued to trade with the West Indies.\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Master\n! Owner\n! Trade\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1786\n| J.Fowler<br>G.Mitchell\n| Hibbert & Co.\n| London\u2013Jamaica\n|\n|-\n| 1790\n| J.Douglas<br>J.Stroud\n| Hibbert & Co.\n| London\u2013Jamaica\n|\n|-\n| 1795\n| J. Bowen\n| Mestairs\n| London\u2212Tobago\n| Repairs in 1793\n|-\n| 1798\n| J.Gibson<br>C. Clark\n| Brown & Co.\n| London\u2013Antigua<br>London\u2013Southern Fishery\n| Repairs in 1793\n|-\n| 1799\n| C. Clark\n| Bennett<ref name=LR1799>[https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015004281260?urlappend=%3Bseq=208 ''Lloyd's Register'' (1799), Seq.\u2116L38.]</ref>\n| London\u2013Southern Fishery\n| Repairs in 1793\n|-\n|}\n\nIn 1798 the ship-owner Daniel Bennett acquired ''Kingston''.\n\n{{see also|List of ships owned by Daniel Bennett & Son}}\n\n'''1st whaling voyage (1798-1799):''' Captain Charles Clark sailed from England on 11 March 1798, bound for the Pacific Ocean.<ref name=bswf>[https://whalinghistory.org/bv/voyages/ British Southern Whale Fishery Database \u2013 Voyages: ''Kingston''.]</ref>\n\nKingston was reported to have been on the west coast of America early 1799. At [[Cabo Blanco, Peru]],<ref name=ACTJ>{{cite web |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71247621 |title=Arrival of Vessels at Port Jackson, and their Departure |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |work=Australian Town and Country Journal, Saturday 3 January 1891, p.16. |publisher= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> she and another whaler, {{ship||Cornwall|1794 ship|2}}, assisted by ''Sally'', captured ''Nostra Senora de Bethlehem'', which had been sailing from Callao to Guayaquil.<ref>[https://whalinghistory.org/bv/voyages/  British Southern Whale Fishery Database \u2013 Voyages: 'Cornwall''.]</ref> A prize crew from ''Cornwall'' under the command of Meather, ''Cornwall''{{'}}s second mate, brought ''Nostra Senora de Bethlehem'' into Port Jackson on 24 April 1799.<ref>Collins (1804), p.543.</ref><ref name=ACTJ/>{{refn|On 1 May 1799,<ref>Library Committee... (1914), pp.730-1.</ref> the [[Vice admiralty court]] condemned ''Nostra Senora de Bethlehem'' and her cargo.<ref>[https://www.records.nsw.gov.au/archives/collections-and-research/guides-and-indexes/vice-admiralty-court-nsw-1787-1911 NSW State Archives and Records: Vice Admiralty Court of NSW, 1787-1911.]</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nClark returned to England on 12 November 1799.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''2nd whaling voyage (1800-1801):''' Captain Thomas Dennis acquired a [[letter of marque]] on 15 January 1800.<ref name=LoM/> ''Kingston'' was to sail in company with {{ship||Elligood|1794 ship|2}}, which too was a Bennett ship. They were to sail on a speculative voyage to New Holland for whales. They were then to examine King George Sound, proceed to Shark Bay and the north-west coast, and return via Madagascar and southern Africa. The voyage would require them to infringe on the British [[East India Company]]'s (EIC) monopoly on navigation east of the Cape of Good Hope. They received permission from the EIC's Court of Directors on 16 February. ''Kingston'' sailed on 19 February.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n''Elligood'' and ''Kingston'' arrived in [[Cape Town]] on 5 May 1800. The two vessels did some whaling off the African coast and then turned east, cruising off [[Western Australia]] from 9 August to 22 December. On 27 August they were at [[King George Sound]]. There, at the entrance to [[Oyster Harbour, Western Australia]] ({{coord|34|59|37.9|S|117|56|39.8|E}}, Dixson made a small garden and left a copper plate engraved \"Aug. 27 1800. Chr Dixson, ship Elligood\". Late in 1801 [[Matthew Flinders]] found the plate on his way along the southern coast of Australia to [[Port Jackson]].<ref>Richards (1991), pp.35-53.</ref>\n\n''Kingston'' returned to England on 4 December 1801.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''3rd whaling voyage (1802):''' Captain Tristam Bunker sailed from England on 9 February 1802. He returned on 16 December.<ref name=bswf/>\n\nIn 1803 Danniel Bennett sold ''Kingston'' to Alexander and John Gibbon, and Matthew Swain.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''4th whaling voyage (1803\u20131804):''' Captain Matthew Swain sailed on 18 June 1803. He returned on 13 July 1804.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''5th whaling voyage (1804\u20131806):''' Captain Matthew Swain sailed on 27 September 1804, bound for the [[Kerguelen Islands|Isle of Desolation]]. ''Kingston'' was there on 1 April 1805. ''Kingston'' returned to London on 15 June with 1600 barrels of \"black oil\".<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''6th whaling voyage (1806\u20131808):''' Captain Thomas Richards sailed from England on 21 August 1806. He returned on 25 May 1808.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''7th whaling voyage (1808\u20131809):''' Captain Thomas Richards sailed from England on 5 August 1808. He returned on 13 September 1809.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''8th whaling voyage (1809\u20131811):''' Captain Thomas Richards sailed from England on 20 November 1809. He returned on 16 April 1811.<ref name=bswf/> ''Kingston'' underwent a \"good repair\" that year, presumably after her return.<ref name=RS1815/>\n\n'''9th whaling voyage (1811\u20131813):''' Captain Granville (or William Glanville) sailed from England in 1811. He returned on 18 May 1813.<ref name=bswf/> In 1813 ''Kingston'' underwent a \"good repair\".<ref name=RS1815/>\n\n'''Transport:''' The ''Register of Shipping'' for 1815 shows ''Kingston'' with Richardson, master, and trade London transport.<ref name=RS1815>[https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015024214275?urlappend=%3Bseq=395  ''Register of Shipping'' (1815), Seq.\u2116K65.]</ref>\n\n'''10th whaling voyage (1815-c.1817):''' Captain Joplin or John Jopling sailed from England on 21 December 1815. At some point her master changed to James Young.<ref name=bswf/>\n\nThe ''Register of Shipping'' for 1818 showed ''Kingston''{{'}}s master changing from J. Topplen to Young, and her trade from London\u2212Southern Fishery to London\u2212Quebec.<ref name=RS1818>[https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015024214259?urlappend=%3Bseq=373 ''Register of Shipping'' (1818), Seq.\u2116K65.]</ref>\n\n==Fate==\n''Kingston'' was last listed in 1819. ''Lloyd's Register'' and the ''Register of Shipping'' both showed her master as J.Young, her owner as Gibbon, and her trade as London\u2013Quebec.\n\n==Notes, citations, and references==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n'''References'''\n* Clayton, Jane M. (2014) ''Ships employed in the South Sea Whale Fishery from Britain: 1775-1815: An alphabetical list of ships''. (Berforts Group). {{ISBN|9781908616524}}\n* Collins, David (1804) ''On Account of the English Colony in New South Wales, from Its First Settlement in January 1788, to August 1801 ... To which are Added, Some Particulars of New Zealand ... and an Account of a Voyage ... by which the Existence of a Strait Separating Van Diemen's Land from the Continent of New Holland was Ascertained''. (Cadell)\n* Library Committee of the Commonwealth Parliament, ''[[Historical Records of Australia]]''.\n* Richards, Rhys (1991) \"The cruise of the 'Kingston and the Elligood' in 1800 and the wreck found on King Island in 1802\". ''The Great Circle'', Vol. 13, No. 1, pp. 35-53\n* Stanbury, Myra, Kandy-Jane Henderson, Bernard Derrien, Nicolas Bigourdan, & Evelyne Le Touze (2015) \"Chapter 18: Epilogue\" [online]. In: Stanbury, Myra. ''The Mermaid Atoll Shipwreck: A Mysterious Early 19th-century Loss''. (Fremantle, WA: Australian National Centre of Excellence for Maritime Archaeology and the Australasian Institute for Maritime Archaeology): 235-290. [https://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=829245882825003;res=IELENG] {{ISBN|9781876465094}} [cited 20 Aug 18].\n\n[[Category:1780 ships]]\n[[Category:Age of Sail merchant ships of England]]\n[[Category:Whaling ships]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|Kingston (ship)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2018}}\n{| {{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image =\n| Ship caption =\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship country=United Kingdom\n| Ship flag={{shipboxflag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n| Ship name = ''Kingston''\n| Ship namesake =\n| Ship owner =*1780:J. Collard\n* 1798:D. Bennett\n* 1803: Alexander & John Gibbon; Matthew Swain\n| Ship operator =\n| Ship ordered =\n| Ship builder = Bristol\n| Ship original cost =\n| Ship laid down =\n| Ship launched = 1780\n| Ship acquired =\n| Ship commissioned =\n| Ship decommissioned =\n| Ship in service =\n| Ship out of service =\n| Ship renamed =\n| Ship struck =\n| Ship reinstated =\n| Ship honours =\n| Ship honors =\n| Ship captured =\n| Ship fate = Last listed 1819\n| Ship status =\n| Ship notes =\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header =\n| Header caption =\n| Ship class =\n| Ship tons burthen=287,<ref name=LoM>[http://www.1812privateers.org/Great%20Britain/marque1793-1815.pdf Letter of Marque, p.71 - accessed 25 July 2017.]</ref> or 293,<ref name=LR1799/> or 300<ref name=LR1780/><ref name=RS1818/> ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]])\n| Ship length ={{cvt|95|ft|0|in|m|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=Stanbury>Stanbury ''et al.'' (2015), App.7.</ref>\n| Ship beam ={{cvt|27|ft|3|in|m|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=Stanbury/>\n| Ship draught =\n| Ship draft =\n| Ship hold depth =\n| Ship propulsion =\n| Ship sail plan =\n| Ship complement =*1800:26<ref name=LoM/>\n* 1803:18\n| Ship armament =*1780:20 \u00d7 9-pounder + 4 \u00d7 6-pounder guns<ref name=LR1780/>\n* 1799:2 \u00d7 4-pounder guns + 10 \u00d7 9-pounder [[carronades]]<ref name=LR1799/>\n* 1800:12 \u00d7 9&4-pounder cannons<ref name=LoM/>\n* 1815:8 \u00d7 6-pounder [[carronades]]<ref name=RS1815/>\n| Ship notes = Two decks and three masts\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Kingston''''' was launched at Bristol in 1780 as a [[West Indiaman]]. From 1798 she made ten voyages as a whaler. She then briefly sailed between England and Quebec, and is last listed in 1819.\n\n==Career==\n''Kingston'' first appeared in ''[[Lloyd's Register]]'' in 1780 with J. Fowler, master, J. Collard, owner, and trade Bristol\u2013Jamaica.<ref name=LR1780>[https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015065522800?urlappend=%3Bseq=162 ''Lloyd's Register'' (1780), \"K\" Supple. pages, Seq. \u2116K80.]</ref> For the next 18 or so years she continued to trade with the West Indies.\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Master\n! Owner\n! Trade\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1786\n| J.Fowler<br>G.Mitchell\n| Hibbert & Co.\n| London\u2013Jamaica\n|\n|-\n| 1790\n| J.Douglas<br>J.Stroud\n| Hibbert & Co.\n| London\u2013Jamaica\n|\n|-\n| 1795\n| J. Bowen\n| Mestairs\n| London\u2212Tobago\n| Repairs in 1793\n|-\n| 1798\n| J.Gibson<br>C. Clark\n| Brown & Co.\n| London\u2013Antigua<br>London\u2013Southern Fishery\n| Repairs in 1793\n|-\n| 1799\n| C. Clark\n| Bennett<ref name=LR1799>[https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015004281260?urlappend=%3Bseq=208 ''Lloyd's Register'' (1799), Seq.\u2116L38.]</ref>\n| London\u2013Southern Fishery\n| Repairs in 1793\n|-\n|}\n\nIn 1798 the ship-owner Daniel Bennett acquired ''Kingston''.\n\n{{see also|List of ships owned by Daniel Bennett & Son}}\n\n'''1st whaling voyage (1798-1799):''' Captain Charles Clark sailed from England on 11 March 1798, bound for the Pacific Ocean.<ref name=bswf>[https://whalinghistory.org/bv/voyages/ British Southern Whale Fishery Database \u2013 Voyages: ''Kingston''.]</ref>\n\nKingston was reported to have been on the west coast of America early 1799. At [[Cabo Blanco, Peru]],<ref name=ACTJ>{{cite web |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71247621 |title=Arrival of Vessels at Port Jackson, and their Departure |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |work=Australian Town and Country Journal, Saturday 3 January 1891, p.16. |publisher= |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> she and another whaler, {{ship||Cornwall|1794 ship|2}}, assisted by ''Sally'', captured ''Nostra Senora de Bethlehem'', which had been sailing from Callao to Guayaquil.<ref>[https://whalinghistory.org/bv/voyages/  British Southern Whale Fishery Database \u2013 Voyages: 'Cornwall''.]</ref> A prize crew from ''Cornwall'' under the command of Meather, ''Cornwall''{{'}}s second mate, brought ''Nostra Senora de Bethlehem'' into Port Jackson on 24 April 1799.<ref>Collins (1804), p.543.</ref><ref name=ACTJ/>{{refn|On 1 May 1799,<ref>Library Committee... (1914), pp.730-1.</ref> the [[Vice admiralty court]] condemned ''Nostra Senora de Bethlehem'' and her cargo.<ref>[https://www.records.nsw.gov.au/archives/collections-and-research/guides-and-indexes/vice-admiralty-court-nsw-1787-1911 NSW State Archives and Records: Vice Admiralty Court of NSW, 1787-1911.]</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nClark returned to England on 12 November 1799.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''2nd whaling voyage (1800-1801):''' Captain Thomas Dennis acquired a [[letter of marque]] on 15 January 1800.<ref name=LoM/> ''Kingston'' was to sail in company with {{ship||Elligood|1794 ship|2}}, which too was a Bennett ship. They were to sail on a speculative voyage to New Holland for whales. They were then to examine King George Sound, proceed to Shark Bay and the north-west coast, and return via Madagascar and southern Africa. The voyage would require them to infringe on the British [[East India Company]]'s (EIC) monopoly on navigation east of the Cape of Good Hope. They received permission from the EIC's Court of Directors on 16 February. ''Kingston'' sailed on 19 February.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n''Elligood'' and ''Kingston'' arrived in [[Cape Town]] on 5 May 1800. The two vessels did some whaling off the African coast and then turned east, cruising off [[Western Australia]] from 9 August to 22 December. On 27 August they were at [[King George Sound]]. There, at the entrance to [[Oyster Harbour, Western Australia]] ({{coord|34|59|37.9|S|117|56|39.8|E}}, Dixson made a small garden and left a copper plate engraved \"Aug. 27 1800. Chr Dixson, ship Elligood\". Late in 1801 [[Matthew Flinders]] found the plate on his way along the southern coast of Australia to [[Port Jackson]].<ref>Richards (1991), pp.35-53.</ref>\n\n''Kingston'' returned to England on 4 December 1801.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''3rd whaling voyage (1802):''' Captain Tristam Bunker sailed from England on 9 February 1802. He returned on 16 December.<ref name=bswf/>\n\nIn 1803 Danniel Bennett sold ''Kingston'' to Alexander and John Gibbon, and Matthew Swain.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''4th whaling voyage (1803\u20131804):''' Captain Matthew Swain sailed on 18 June 1803. He returned on 13 July 1804.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''5th whaling voyage (1804\u20131806):''' Captain Matthew Swain sailed on 27 September 1804, bound for the [[Kerguelen Islands|Isle of Desolation]]. ''Kingston'' was there on 1 April 1805. ''Kingston'' returned to London on 15 June with 1600 barrels of \"black oil\".<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''6th whaling voyage (1806\u20131808):''' Captain Thomas Richards sailed from England on 21 August 1806. He returned on 25 May 1808.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''7th whaling voyage (1808\u20131809):''' Captain Thomas Richards sailed from England on 5 August 1808. He returned on 13 September 1809.<ref name=bswf/>\n\n'''8th whaling voyage (1809\u20131811):''' Captain Thomas Richards sailed from England on 20 November 1809. He returned on 16 April 1811.<ref name=bswf/> ''Kingston'' underwent a \"good repair\" that year, presumably after her return.<ref name=RS1815/>\n\n'''9th whaling voyage (1811\u20131813):''' Captain Granville (or William Glanville) sailed from England in 1811. He returned on 18 May 1813.<ref name=bswf/> In 1813 ''Kingston'' underwent a \"good repair\".<ref name=RS1815/>\n\n'''Transport:''' The ''Register of Shipping'' for 1815 shows ''Kingston'' with Richardson, master, and trade London transport.<ref name=RS1815>[https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015024214275?urlappend=%3Bseq=395  ''Register of Shipping'' (1815), Seq.\u2116K65.]</ref>\n\n'''10th whaling voyage (1815-c.1817):''' Captain Joplin or John Jopling sailed from England on 21 December 1815. At some point her master changed to James Young.<ref name=bswf/>\n\nThe ''Register of Shipping'' for 1818 showed ''Kingston''{{'}}s master changing from J. Topplen to Young, and her trade from London\u2212Southern Fishery to London\u2212Quebec.<ref name=RS1818>[https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015024214259?urlappend=%3Bseq=373 ''Register of Shipping'' (1818), Seq.\u2116K65.]</ref>\n\n==Fate==\n''Kingston'' was last listed in 1819. ''Lloyd's Register'' and the ''Register of Shipping'' both showed her master as J.Young, her owner as Gibbon, and her trade as London\u2013Quebec.\n\n==Notes, citations, and references==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n'''References'''\n* Clayton, Jane M. (2014) ''Ships employed in the South Sea Whale Fishery from Britain: 1775-1815: An alphabetical list of ships''. (Berforts Group). {{ISBN|9781908616524}}\n* Collins, David (1804) ''On Account of the English Colony in New South Wales, from Its First Settlement in January 1788, to August 1801 ... To which are Added, Some Particulars of New Zealand ... and an Account of a Voyage ... by which the Existence of a Strait Separating Van Diemen's Land from the Continent of New Holland was Ascertained''. (Cadell)\n* Library Committee of the Commonwealth Parliament, ''[[Historical Records of Australia]]''.\n* Richards, Rhys (1991) \"The cruise of the 'Kingston and the Elligood' in 1800 and the wreck found on King Island in 1802\". ''The Great Circle'', Vol. 13, No. 1, pp. 35-53\n* Stanbury, Myra, Kandy-Jane Henderson, Bernard Derrien, Nicolas Bigourdan, & Evelyne Le Touze (2015) \"Chapter 18: Epilogue\" [online]. In: Stanbury, Myra. ''The Mermaid Atoll Shipwreck: A Mysterious Early 19th-century Loss''. (Fremantle, WA: Australian National Centre of Excellence for Maritime Archaeology and the Australasian Institute for Maritime Archaeology): 235-290. [[https://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=829245882825003;res=IELENG] {{ISBN|9781876465094}} [cited 20 Aug 18].\n\n[[Category:1780 ships]]\n[[Category:Age of Sail merchant ships of England]]\n[[Category:Whaling ships]]\n", "name_user": "Desb42", "label": "safe", "comment": "balance link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kingston_(1780_ship)"}
